      • emptyIterator

        public static <E> Iterator<E> emptyIterator()
        Returns the empty Iterator for a particular type (type-safe). Note that unlike this method, the like-named static field does not provide type safety.
        Type Parameters:
        E - the type of the Iterator's elements.
        Returns:
        the empty Iterator.

      • concat

        public static <E> Iterator<E> concat(Iterator<? extends E>... iterators)
        Concatenates all the given Iterators into a single one. The source Iterators aren't polled until necessary. The returned Iterator supports Iterator.remove() when the corresponding input Iterator supports it.
        Type Parameters:
        E - the type of the returned Iterator's elements.
        Parameters:
        iterators - the Iterators to concatenate.
        Returns:
        the concatenated Iterator.
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if iterators is null or if it contains a null reference.

      • cycle

        public static <E> Iterator<E> cycle(Iterator<? extends E> iterator)

        Type Parameters:
        E - the type of the returned Iterator's elements.
        Parameters:
        iterator - the source Iterator.
        Returns:
        the cyclic Iterator.
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if iterator is null.

      • limit

        public static <E> Iterator<E> limit(Iterator<? extends E> iterator,
                                    int limit)
        Creates an Iterator returning only the first limit elements of the given Iterator. The source Iterator is not polled until necessary. The returned Iterator supports Iterator.remove() if the source Iterator supports it.
        Type Parameters:
        E - the type of the returned Iterator's elements.
        Parameters:
        iterator - the Iterator to limit.
        limit - the number of elements in the returned Iterator.
        Returns:
        the limited Iterator.
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if iterator is null.
        IllegalArgumentException - if (limit is negative.
